		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Running Famicom carts in a NES</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Many Gyromite carts with 5 screws have adapters inside. In addition to the 5 screws, the cart connector is also important for identifying adapters, as illustrated in <a href="http://www.racketboy.com/retro/hacks/gyromite-nes-import-adapter-guide" class="postlink">this page</a>.  I had to go through a few Gyromite carts before I found 2 that had adapters in them, and those were the 2 that had both characteristics: 5 screws and little lines extending from the side of the connector pins.<br /><br />Unfortunately there are very few Gyromite carts available on MercadoLivre right now, and the connectors are not visible in any of the pictures (plus, the carts are expensive as shit!).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


