		<td><b>Re: Running Famicom carts in a NES</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I don't recommand the Gyromite adapter AT ALL.<br /><br />I had to import a Gyromite cart all the way from USA just to get the adapter, and now it's eating dust in a drawer half destroyed somewhere. Because it's really impractical, ideally you'd have to place the PCB in the NES cart, and close it again and use it as a normal NES cart, but this only works for NROM-like Famicom PCBs, not very useful. Otherwise you'll have to deal with a bare PCB and trying to insert it into your NES, which is a terribly hard and annoying thing to do for both the front loader (you don't see what you're doing) and toploader (the connector is protected by a &quot;clapet&quot; (I have no idea how this word translate in english), and is hard to access )<br /><br />So if you want to be &quot;confortable&quot; get a real adapter and forget about Gyromite. The Gyromite game is absolutely terrible by the way, so at least you don't feel bad to destroy it ^^

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


